t2049.text: For as much shit as #StarTrekDiscovery gets (often deserved), it has stepped up to the challenge of showing us the excitement of stepping into a bigger universe on a couple of occasions. The fans will love Picard because it plays it safer as a character study of a beloved Capt.

t2050.text: And that's not necessarily a bad thing. Wrath of Kahn is still the only great Star Trek film. There are great stories to be told about viewing the awe and wonder of discovery framed through a protagonists life experience. But Star Trek started out as being bigger than that.

t2051.text: From Star Trek 2: The Wrath of Kahn onwards, Star Trek became focused on discovering the universe through the lens of our protagonists sense of self. They aren't exploring the Universe - they're exploring their own human experience.

t2052.text: The problem with #StarTrekPicard is the same problem I've had with Star Trek since the first movies: it often neglects the raison d'être of the franchise. Star Trek is about discovering humanity through exploring the universe and not the shows navel.
